A RESOLUTION
1 Recognizing and commending Handy Johnson, Jr.; and for other purposes.
2 WHEREAS, Handy Johnson, Jr., has long been recognized by the citizens of this state for
3 the vital role that he has played in leadership and his deep personal commitment to the
4 welfare of the citizens of Georgia; and
5 WHEREAS, he has diligently and conscientiously devoted innumerable hours of his time,
6 talents, and energy toward the betterment of his community and state as evidenced
7 dramatically by his superlative service within the West End Neighborhood; and
8 WHEREAS, in 1971, Handy and his late wife Lois purchased and restored a historic house
9 in West End, and along with their two daughters, Jessica and Ursula, The Johnson's made this
10 neighborhood their home; and
11 WHEREAS, Handy enrolled in the University of Georgia College of Environment and
12 Design and received a master's degree in landscape architecture, making history as the first
13 African American to be awarded a graduate degree from that program; and
